<script type="application/ld+json">
{"@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "FAQPage", "mainEntity": [
{"@type": "Question", "name": "What must a Subchapter V plan contain?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "A Sub V plan must include a brief history of the business, a liquidation analysis, projected financial information, and the proposed treatment for each class of claims. Unlike traditional Chapter 11, no separate disclosure statement is required."}},
{"@type": "Question", "name": "When must the Sub V plan be filed?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The plan must be filed within 90 days after the order for relief (11 U.S.C. section 1189(b)). Extensions are possible for cause, but courts expect compliance with this deadline."}},
{"@type": "Question", "name": "Can creditors file a competing plan in Subchapter V?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "No. Only the debtor may file a plan in Subchapter V. This is one of the biggest advantages over traditional Chapter 11, where creditors can propose competing plans after the exclusivity period expires."}},
{"@type": "Question", "name": "What happens if creditors reject the Sub V plan?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The court can still confirm the plan under section 1191(b) (cramdown) if the plan does not discriminate unfairly, is fair and equitable, and commits all projected disposable income to unsecured creditors for 3-5 years."}},
{"@type": "Question", "name": "Does a Sub V plan require a disclosure statement?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "No. Section 1181(b) eliminates the disclosure statement requirement for Subchapter V cases. The plan itself must contain adequate information, but no separate disclosure document needs court approval before soliciting votes."}}
]}
</script>
